  "name": "Seven Rays — Ancient Roots",
  "description": "The seven rays as a cosmological system, rooted in the Vedic tradition of Surya's seven horses and the universal pattern of sevenfold differentiation found across Hindu, Buddhist, Kabbalistic, and Gnostic traditions. This grammar centers the ancient geometry: seven qualities of the One Light, each governing a plane of existence, their weaving creating the fabric of manifest reality. It is not a personality typing system or a developmental hierarchy — it is a map of how spirit becomes matter and matter returns to spirit.\n\nThe seven rays predate any modern interpreter. In the Rig Veda, Surya's chariot is drawn by seven horses whose names describe qualities of solar force. Blavatsky (The Secret Doctrine, 1888) traced the pattern across civilizations. This grammar presents the rays as they appear across traditions — letting the geometric correspondences speak for themselves.\n\nThis is the foundational grammar in a planned Seven Rays family (like the I Ching grammar family), with future grammars exploring Bailey's psychological typology, Leadbeater's Master correspondences, and the Vedic source texts directly.\n\nPUBLIC DOMAIN ILLUSTRATION REFERENCES: Hindu temple sculptures of Surya's chariot with seven horses (Konark Sun Temple, 13th century). Tibetan Buddhist thangka paintings of the Five Dhyani Buddhas. Kabbalistic Tree of Life diagrams from Athanasius Kircher's Oedipus Aegyptiacus (1652). Robert Fludd's cosmological diagrams from Utriusque Cosmi (1617). Illustrations from Blavatsky's Secret Doctrine (1888). Medieval manuscript illuminations of the seven planetary spheres.",
  "grammar_type": "custom",
